  "time_ut": 1660827210,
  "original_lang": "si",
  "original_title": "\u0db8\u0dc4 \u0db6\u0dd0\u0d82\u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dc0 \u0db4\u0ddc\u0dbd\u0dd3 \u0d85\u0db1\u0dd4\u0db4\u0dcf\u0dad \u0dc0\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dc3\u0dca \u0db1\u0ddc\u0d9a\u0dbb\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "The central bank does not change interest rates",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The Monetary Board of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka in its meeting held on 17th August 2022 has decided to maintain the Fixed Deposit Facility Rate (SDFR) and the Fixed Lending Facility Rate (SLFR) of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka at the current level of 14.50 percent and 15.50 percent respectively.",
        "In arriving at this decision, the Central Bank informs that the Monetary Board considered forecasts based on the latest data, which indicated a larger-than-expected contraction in economic activity and a faster-than-expected easing of price pressures compared to the last monetary policy commentary.",
        "Due to the tight monetary and fiscal policies that are already in place as well as the measures to limit non-essential import expenditure, it is expected that the credit given to the private sector will decrease significantly in the near term and there is also a risk of rising unemployment, says the Central Bank.",
        "Although surface inflation is forecast to remain high in the near term, the policy measures taken so far by the central bank and the government will help control overall demand pressures, as well as the expected decline in global commodity prices and the resulting domestic prices in the near term. The monetary board is also of the opinion that the inflation expectations will be controlled by reducing the numbers."
      ],
